[Category:Japanese drama films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:Japanese film remakes]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kon Ichikawa]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Kon Ichikawa]]\n{{2000s-Japan-film-stub}}\n{{2000s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Inugamis_(2006_film)"}
{"title_page": "French corvette Aurore (1766)", "text_new": "{{Other ships|French ship Aurore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=''Aurore''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:Courtanvaux 3.jpg|200px|]]\n|Ship caption=Portrait of ''Aurore'' by [[Nicolas Ozanne]] (drawing) and [[Elisabeth Haussard]] (engraving)\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|border|45px|French Navy Ensign]] \n|Ship name=*''Aurore''\n*''Petite Aurore''<ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Le Havre<ref name=Demerliac>Demerliac, n\u00b0566, p.74</ref>\n|Ship laid down=1766 <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship launched= April 1767 <ref name=Roche>Roche, p.350</ref> or May 1767 <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship acquired= \n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=''Petite Aurore'', 1768 <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship struck=1775\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=corvette\n|Ship type=\n|Ship displacement=130 tons (French) <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship length=21.6 metres<ref name=Roche /> (66'6\" French feet<ref name=Demerliac />) overall\n|Ship beam=5.9 metres<ref name=Roche /> (18'1\" French feet<ref name=Demerliac />)\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship hold depth=2.3 metres<ref name=Roche /> (8\"2' French feet<ref name=Demerliac />)\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship propulsion=[[Sails]]\n|Ship complement=30 to 40 men <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship armament=6 \u00d7 2 or 3-pounder guns <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Aurore''''' was a corvette or [[Snow (ship)|snow]], designed by [[Nicolas Ozanne]].<ref name=Demerliac /> Built privately on the personal funds of [[Fran\u00e7ois-C\u00e9sar Le Tellier de Courtanvaux]], she was commissioned by the French Navy<ref name=Roche /> and used for scientific purposes.<ref name=ancre>{{Cite web|url=https://ancre.fr/en/monograph/64-monographie-de-l-aurore-corvette-1766.html|title=MONOGRAPHIE DE L'AURORE - Corvette -1766|website=Ancre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> She performed the [[History of longitude|first measurement of longitude]] using [[Marine chronometer]].<ref name=ancre />\n\n== Background ==\n{{See also|History of longitude}}\nDuring the 18th century, measure of longitude was performed by comparing the [[solar time]] of the ship with that of a know point, the difference in time being in relation with displacement on the globe. In practice, this was achieved by keeping the time of the latest point of departure by mean of [[hourglass]]es, and by tracking the moment the sun was seen at its [[zenith]]. However, hourglasses had a poor precision because they needed to be turned by hand at exact intervals, because sand tended aggregate due to humidity, and because its flow eroded the thin section of the bulb, accelerating the flow. Mechanical clocks were seen as the logical next step in technology, and in 1722, eight years after the British introduced [[Longitude rewards]], the [[French Academy of Sciences]] started offering a prize every two year for the best chronometer for sea navigation.<ref name=Delacroix6>Delacroix, p. 6</ref> \n\nIn 1766, clockmaker [[Pierre Le Roy]] submitted a marine chronometer for consideration for the 1767 prize. At the time, several several other clockmakers in France were trying to develop similar instruments, notably [[Ferdinand Berthoud]], [[\u00c9tienne Tavernier]] and [[Jean Romilly]], but being unfinished or damaged at the time, their prototypes could not contest. Finging Le Roy's invention promising, the Academy started studying ways to test it in real conditions at sea. [[Fran\u00e7ois-C\u00e9sar Le Tellier de Courtanvaux|Courtanvaux]], who sat at the Academy, then proposed to shoulder the cost of the tests himself by having a ship built specially for the occasion.<ref name=Delacroix6 />\n{{gallery\n |align=center \n |title=Le Roy's chonometre\n |File:Pierre Le Roy chronometer 1766.jpg|Le Roy's chonometre on display at CnAM\n |File:Pierre Le Roy chronometer mechanism 1766.jpg|Mechanism of Le Roy's chonometre\n}}\n\nThe expedition was depart [[Le Havre]] and cruise off the Northern coast of France, sailing to various harbours \u2014 [[Calais]], [[Dunkirk]], [[Rotterdam]], [[Brielle]] and [[Amsterdam]] \u2014 before returning to Boulogne and Le Havre.<ref name=Delacroix10>Delacroix, p. 10</ref> A second journey was to be undertaken in 1768 to the South up to A Coru\u00f1a.<ref name=Delacroix9>Delacroix, p. 9</ref>  The frequent calls were to allow recalibrating the chronometer often, entailing that the ship had to be specially chartered for the purpose and be small and manoeuverable enough to enter all the ports; this precluded use of a regular merchantman, which would in any case have been slow and whose accommodations would have been ill-suited to the purpose. Rather than re-amenaging a merchantman Courtanvaux decided to commission [[Nicolas Ozanne]] to design a corvette-sized yacht.<ref name=Delacroix7>Delacroix, p. 7</ref> Ozanne designed her as a pleasure craft, and the scientists involved in the expedition had quarters of an unusually high quality for the time.<ref name=ancre />\n\nCourtanvaux obtained official support for his endeavour, notably gaining recommendation letters from the [[List of Naval Ministers of France|Secretary of State for the Navy]] for his passage in the Netherlands, and obtaining the status of \"royal frigate\" \u2014 with special dispensation to fly the [[French ensigns|all-white royal ensign]] normally reserved for naval ships.<ref name=Delacroix7 />\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Map Aurore journey-31414882583 b10628de42 b.jpg|thumb|Map of the journey of ''Aurore'' in [[English Channel|the Channel]] and in the [[North Sea]].]]\nOn 19 April 1767, Mathieu Chopin was appointed captain of ''Aurore'' by a royal edict. In the morning of 14 May, ''Aurore'' put to sail for her first trials, watched by the numerous officials, the guarrison and a large crowd. She was deemed a successful vessel, and in the next days her 24-man crew started training and getting accustomed to the ship, while the scientists started calibrating their instruments in a laboratory on the set up on the port.<ref name=Delacroix9 /> Along with his chronometer, Le Roy brought a second prototype, which he did not initially enter in the competition, as its had not been fully tested yet.<ref name=Delacroix9 />\n\nOn 21 May, ''Aurore'' attempted the first leg of her journey, bound for Calais, but a gale forced her to return to Le Havre and wait several days for more clement weather. On 25 May, she departed again, reaching Calais the next morning through bad weather that left the passengers and the crew shaken. The weather taking another turn for the worse, ''Aurore'' remained in Calais for several days. On 6 June, in the early morning, she departed for Dunkirk, where she arrived in the late afternoon, threatened by yet another storm.<ref name=Delacroix10 /> On 13, the passengers were able to go ashore in a boat, enabling measurements to be made on the ground. ''Aurore'' departed Dunkirk on 20, and arrived in Rotterdam during the night. Again, the watches were sent ashore for precise measurements, and Courtanvaux left to visit the Netherland. Meanwhile, ''Aurore'' left Rotterdam on 29 June and sailed on the [[Meuse]] river to Brielle. <ref name=Delacroix11>Delacroix, p. 11</ref>\n\nAt Brielle, Le Roy stated that after testing, the second prototype seemed more reliable than the first, and he offered it to [[Jean-Baptiste de La Chapelle|La Chapelle]]'s consideration. ''Aurore'' was trapped by unfavourable winds that had prevented navigation for a week, and in the night of 6 July, she attempted to seize a passing opportunity to depart; however, a man went overboard, to be saved in the nick of time by a fellow sailor, then ''Aurore'' collided with a Dutch merchantman, and eventually the wind pushed her to the shore. She then aborted her attempt, and returned to port. She finally left on 8 July, arriving in Amsterdam on 11 after sustaining such bad weather that her guns would touch the water and that Le Roy measured a 25\u00b0 list. At Amsterdam, she was rejoined by Courtanvaux, and the scientific staff went ashore again to test their instruments and take precise measurements. <ref name=Delacroix11 />\n\nOn 22 July, ''Aurore'' departed Amsterdam, bound for [[Den Helder]], while Courtanvaux persued his touristic endeavours ashore. They met again at Texel on 25, where ''Aurore'' was again trapped by bad weather until 3 August. In the night of 4 August, she observed an [[aurora]], and in the afternoon of 6 August, she arrived at Boulogne. In the evening, the scientists attempted to disembark on boats, but a sudden gale forced ''Aurore'' to return out at sea. She eventually entered Boulogne harbour the next day. Then, the scientists went ashore for another round of measurements and calibration. On 28 August, ''Aurore'' finally reached Le Havre.<ref name=Delacroix12>Delacroix, p. 12</ref>\n\nIn 1769, the French Royal Navy acquired ''Aurore''.<ref name=ancre />\n\n==Fate==\n''Aurore'' was struck in Brest in 1775.<ref name=Demerliac />\n\n==Legacy==\nAfter the journey, Courtanvaux wrote the story of the expedition. The narration was edited by [[Alexandre Guy Pingr\u00e9|Pingr\u00e9]] and [[Charles Messier|Messier]], illustrated by Ozanne (with notably a representation of the launch of the frigate and a map of the journey), and published in 1768.<ref name=Delacroix9 />\n\nLe Roy's chonometer was found to have accumulated an error of 4 minutes and 52 seconds in the 52 days of the outbound journey, and 51 on the return leg. The second chronometer had an error of only 15 seconds and a half. It was tested again on a naval frigate, [[French frigate Enjou\u00e9e (1766)|''Enjou\u00e9e'']], and in 1769 Le Roy was awarded the prize.<ref name=Delacroix12 /> The chronometer went on to be part of the collections of the [[Conservatoire national des arts et m\u00e9tiers]], where it is on display.<ref>[http://cugnot.cnam.fr:8000/SEARCH/BASIS/collec/internet/objet/DDW?W%3DAUT+PH+WORDS+%27Le+Roy%27+ORDER+BY+DESIG/Ascend%26M%3D5%26K%3D366%26R%3DY%26U%3D1 CHRONOMETRE DE MARINE PAR PIERRE LE ROY], CnAM</ref>\n\nA large scale model of ''Aurore'' is on display at [[Sainte-Genevi\u00e8ve Library]]. The model was made by former sailors of the expedition, and is built as a large 1/12th scale, yielding very minute details.<ref name=ancre /> A few pieces, such as boats and artillery pieces, have disappeared over time.<ref name=ancre />\n{{gallery\n |align=center \n |title=1/12th scale model on display at [[Sainte-Genevi\u00e8ve Library]]\n |File:Corvette Aurore-IMG 9601-white.jpg|Portrait of the model\n |File:Corvette Aurore-IMG 9599.JPG|\n}}\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===References===\n* {{cite book|title=Journal du voyage de M. le Marquis de Courtanvaux sur la fr\u00e9gate l'Aurore, pour essayer par ordre de l'Acad\u00e9mie, plusieurs instrumens relatifs \u00e0 la Longitude|last=Le Tellier de Courtanvaux|first=Fran\u00e7ois-C\u00e9sar|author-link=Fran\u00e7ois-C\u00e9sar Le Tellier de Courtanvaux|date=1768|publisher=Imprimerie royale|language=French|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=hzEAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP9&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false}}\n* {{cite book|title=Corvette l'Aurore, con\u00e7ue par Nicolas Ozanne, r\u00e9alis\u00e9e par le constructeur Bonvoisin|last=Delacroix|first=G\u00e9rard|author-link=G\u00e9rard Delacroix|date=June 2000|publisher=\u00c9ditions Ancre|isbn=2-903179-23-9|language=French|series=Collection Arch\u00e9ologie navale fran\u00e7aise}}\n* {{cite book|title=La Marine de Louis XV: Nomenclature des Navires Fran\u00e7ais de 1715 \u00e0 1774|last=Demerliac|first=Alain|year=2004|publisher=\u00c9ditions Ancre|isbn=2-906381-19-5|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean-Michel|last=Roche|year=2005|title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours|isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6|oclc=165892922|publisher=Group Retozel-Maury Millau|volume=1|page=350}} (1671-1870)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aurore (1766)}}\n[[Category:1767 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other ships|French ship Aurore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=''Aurore''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:Courtanvaux 3.jpg|200px|]]\n|Ship caption=Portrait of ''Aurore'' by [[Nicolas Ozanne]] (drawing) and [[Elisabeth Haussard]] (engraving)\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|border|45px|French Navy Ensign]] \n|Ship name=*''Aurore''\n*''Petite Aurore''<ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Le Havre<ref name=Demerliac>Demerliac, n\u00b0566, p.74</ref>\n|Ship laid down=1766 <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship launched= April 1767 <ref name=Roche>Roche, p.350</ref> or May 1767 <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship acquired= \n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=''Petite Aurore'', 1768 <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship struck=1775\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=corvette\n|Ship type=\n|Ship displacement=130 tons (French) <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship length=21.6 metres<ref name=Roche /> (66'6\" French feet<ref name=Demerliac />) overall\n|Ship beam=5.9 metres<ref name=Roche /> (18'1\" French feet<ref name=Demerliac />)\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship hold depth=2.3 metres<ref name=Roche /> (8\"2' French feet<ref name=Demerliac />)\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship propulsion=[[Sails]]\n|Ship complement=30 to 40 men <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship armament=6 \u00d7 2 or 3-pounder guns <ref name=Demerliac />\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Aurore''''' was a corvette or [[Snow (ship)|snow]], designed by [[Nicolas Ozanne]].<ref name=Demerliac /> Built privately on the personal funds of [[Fran\u00e7ois-C\u00e9sar Le Tellier de Courtanvaux]], she was commissioned by the French Navy<ref name=Roche /> and used for scientific purposes.<ref name=ancre>{{Cite web|url=https://ancre.fr/en/monograph/64-monographie-de-l-aurore-corvette-1766.html|title=MONOGRAPHIE DE L'AURORE - Corvette -1766|website=Ancre|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> She performed the [[History of longitude|first measurement of longitude]] using [[Marine chronometer]].<ref name=ancre />\n\n== Background ==\n{{See also|History of longitude}}\nDuring the 18th century, measure of longitude was performed by comparing the [[solar time]] of the ship with that of a know point, the difference in time being in relation with displacement on the globe. In practice, this was achieved by keeping the time of the latest point of departure by mean of [[hourglass]]es, and by tracking the moment the sun was seen at its [[zenith]]. However, hourglasses had a poor precision because they needed to be turned by hand at exact intervals, because sand tended aggregate due to humidity, and because its flow eroded the thin section of the bulb, accelerating the flow. Mechanical clocks were seen as the logical next step in technology, and in 1722, eight years after the British introduced [[Longitude rewards]], the [[French Academy of Sciences]] started offering a prize every two year for the best chronometer for sea navigation.<ref name=Delacroix6>Delacroix, p. 6</ref> \n\nIn 1766, clockmaker [[Pierre Le Roy]] submitted a marine chronometer for consideration for the 1767 prize. At the time, several several other clockmakers in France were trying to develop similar instruments, notably [[Ferdinand Berthoud]], [[\u00c9tienne Tavernier]] and [[Jean Romilly]], but being unfinished or damaged at the time, their prototypes could not contest. Finging Le Roy's invention promising, the Academy started studying ways to test it in real conditions at sea. [[Fran\u00e7ois-C\u00e9sar Le Tellier de Courtanvaux|Courtanvaux]], who sat at the Academy, then proposed to shoulder the cost of the tests himself by having a ship built specially for the occasion.<ref name=Delacroix6 />\n{{gallery\n |align=center \n |title=Le Roy's chonometre\n |File:Pierre Le Roy chronometer 1766.jpg|Le Roy's chonometre on display at CnAM\n |File:Pierre Le Roy chronometer mechanism 1766.jpg|Mechanism of Le Roy's chonometre\n}}\n\nThe expedition was depart [[Le Havre]] and cruise off the Northern coast of France, sailing to various harbours \u2014 [[Calais]], [[Dunkirk]], [[Rotterdam]], [[Brielle]] and [[Amsterdam]] \u2014 before returning to Boulogne and Le Havre.<ref name=Delacroix10>Delacroix, p. 10</ref> A second journey was to be undertaken in 1768 to the South up to A Coru\u00f1a.<ref name=Delacroix9>Delacroix, p. 9</ref>  The frequent calls were to allow recalibrating the chronometer often, entailing that the ship had to be specially chartered for the purpose and be small and manoeuverable enough to enter all the ports; this precluded use of a regular merchantman, which would in any case have been slow and whose accommodations would have been ill-suited to the purpose. Rather than re-amenaging a merchantman Courtanvaux decided to commission [[Nicolas Ozanne]] to design a corvette-sized yacht.<ref name=Delacroix7>Delacroix, p. 7</ref> Ozanne designed her as a pleasure craft, and the scientists involved in the expedition had quarters of an unusually high quality for the time.<ref name=ancre />\n\nCourtanvaux obtained official support for his endeavour, notably gaining recommendation letters from the [[List of Naval Ministers of France|Secretary of State for the Navy]] for his passage in the Netherlands, and obtaining the status of \"royal frigate\" \u2014 with special dispensation to fly the [[French ensigns|all-white royal ensign]] normally reserved for naval ships.<ref name=Delacroix7 />\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Map Aurore journey-31414882583 b10628de42 b.jpg|thumb|Map of the journey of ''Aurore'' in [[English Channel|the Channel]] and in the [[North Sea]].]]\nOn 19 April 1767, Mathieu Chopin was appointed captain of ''Aurore'' by a royal edict. In the morning of 14 May, ''Aurore'' put to sail for her first trials, watched by the numerous officials, the guarrison and a large crowd. She was deemed a successful vessel, and in the next days her 24-man crew started training and getting accustomed to the ship, while the scientists started calibrating their instruments in a laboratory on the set up on the port.<ref name=Delacroix9 /> Along with his chronometer, Le Roy brought a second prototype, which he did not initially enter in the competition, as its had not been fully tested yet.<ref name=Delacroix9 />\n\nOn 21 May, ''Aurore'' attempted the first leg of her journey, bound for Calais, but a gale forced her to return to Le Havre and wait several days for more clement weather. On 25 May, she departed again, reaching Calais the next morning through bad weather that left the passengers and the crew shaken. The weather taking another turn for the worse, ''Aurore'' remained in Calais for several days. On 6 June, in the early morning, she departed for Dunkirk, where she arrived in the late afternoon, threatened by yet another storm.<ref name=Delacroix10 /> On 13, the passengers were able to go ashore in a boat, enabling measurements to be made on the ground. ''Aurore'' departed Dunkirk on 20, and arrived in Rotterdam during the night. Again, the watches were sent ashore for precise measurements, and Courtanvaux left to visit the Netherland. Meanwhile, ''Aurore'' left Rotterdam on 29 June and sailed on the [[Meuse]] river to Brielle. <ref name=Delacroix11>Delacroix, p. 11</ref>\n\nAt Brielle, Le Roy stated that after testing, the second prototype seemed more reliable than the first, and he offered it to [[Jean-Baptiste de La Chapelle|La Chapelle]]'s consideration. ''Aurore'' was trapped by unfavourable winds that had prevented navigation for a week, and in the night of 6 July, she attempted to seize a passing opportunity to depart; however, a man went overboard, to be saved in the nick of time by a fellow sailor, then ''Aurore'' collided with a Dutch merchantman, and eventually the wind pushed her to the shore. She then aborted her attempt, and returned to port. She finally left on 8 July, arriving in Amsterdam on 11 after sustaining such bad weather that her guns would touch the water and that Le Roy measured a 25\u00b0 list. At Amsterdam, she was rejoined by Courtanvaux, and the scientific staff went ashore again to test their instruments and take precise measurements. <ref name=Delacroix11 />\n\nOn 22 July, ''Aurore'' departed Amsterdam, bound for [[Den Helder]], while Courtanvaux persued his touristic endeavours ashore. They met again at Texel on 25, where ''Aurore'' was again trapped by bad weather until 3 August. In the night of 4 August, she observed an [[aurora]], and in the afternoon of 6 August, she arrived at Boulogne. In the evening, the scientists attempted to disembark on boats, but a sudden gale forced ''Aurore'' to return out at sea. She eventually entered Boulogne harbour the next day. Then, the scientists went ashore for another round of measurements and calibration. On 28 August, ''Aurore'' finally reached Le Havre.<ref name=Delacroix12>Delacroix, p. 12</ref>\n\nIn 1769, the French Royal Navy acquired ''Aurore''.<ref name=ancre />\n\n==Fate==\n''Aurore'' was struck in Brest in 1775.<ref name=Demerliac />\n\n==Legacy==\nAfter the journey, Courtanvaux wrote the story of the expedition. The narration was edited by [[Alexandre Guy Pingr\u00e9|Pingr\u00e9]] and [[Charles Messier|Messier]], illustrated by Ozanne (with notably a representation of the launch of the frigate and a map of the journey), and published in 1768.<ref name=Delacroix9 />\n\nLe Roy's chonometer was found to have accumulated an error of 4 minutes and 52 seconds in the 52 days of the outbound journey, and 51 on the return leg. The second chronometer had an error of only 15 seconds and a half. It was tested again on a naval frigate, [[French frigate Enjou\u00e9e (1766)|''Enjou\u00e9e'']], and in 1769 Le Roy was awarded the prize.<ref name=Delacroix12 /> The chronometer went on to be part of the collections of the [[Conservatoire national des arts et m\u00e9tiers]], where it is on diplay.<ref>[http://cugnot.cnam.fr:8000/SEARCH/BASIS/collec/internet/objet/DDW?W%3DAUT+PH+WORDS+%27Le+Roy%27+ORDER+BY+DESIG/Ascend%26M%3D5%26K%3D366%26R%3DY%26U%3D1 CHRONOMETRE DE MARINE PAR PIERRE LE ROY], CnAM</ref>\n\nA large scale model of ''Aurore'' is on display at [[Sainte-Genevi\u00e8ve Library]]. The model was made by former sailors of the expedition, and is built as a large 1/12th scale, yielding very minute details.<ref name=ancre /> A few pieces, such as boats and artillery pieces, have disappeared over time.<ref name=ancre />\n{{gallery\n |align=center \n |title=1/12th scale model on display at [[Sainte-Genevi\u00e8ve Library]]\n |File:Corvette Aurore-IMG 9601-white.jpg|Portrait of the model\n |File:Corvette Aurore-IMG 9599.JPG|\n}}\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===References===\n* {{cite book|title=Journal du voyage de M. le Marquis de Courtanvaux sur la fr\u00e9gate l'Aurore, pour essayer par ordre de l'Acad\u00e9mie, plusieurs instrumens relatifs \u00e0 la Longitude|last=Le Tellier de Courtanvaux|first=Fran\u00e7ois-C\u00e9sar|author-link=Fran\u00e7ois-C\u00e9sar Le Tellier de Courtanvaux|date=1768|publisher=Imprimerie royale|language=French|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=hzEAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP9&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false}}\n* {{cite book|title=Corvette l'Aurore, con\u00e7ue par Nicolas Ozanne, r\u00e9alis\u00e9e par le constructeur Bonvoisin|last=Delacroix|first=G\u00e9rard|author-link=G\u00e9rard Delacroix|date=June 2000|publisher=\u00c9ditions Ancre|isbn=2-903179-23-9|language=French|series=Collection Arch\u00e9ologie navale fran\u00e7aise}}\n* {{cite book|title=La Marine de Louis XV: Nomenclature des Navires Fran\u00e7ais de 1715 \u00e0 1774|last=Demerliac|first=Alain|year=2004|publisher=\u00c9ditions Ancre|isbn=2-906381-19-5|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean-Michel|last=Roche|year=2005|title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours|isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6|oclc=165892922|publisher=Group Retozel-Maury Millau|volume=1|page=350}} (1671-1870)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aurore (1766)}}\n[[Category:1767 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in France]]\n", "name_user": "Rama", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_corvette_Aurore_(1766)"}
{"title_page": "Buzz Kulik", "text_new": "{{short description|American film director and producer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        =\n| name         = Buzz Kulik\n| birthname    = Seymour Kulik\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1922|7|23}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kearny, New Jersey]], United States\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1999|1|13|1922|7|23}}\n| death_place  = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| occupation   = Film director, film producer\n| yearsactive  = 1949-1992\n}}\n\n'''Seymour \"Buzz\" Kulik''' (July 23, 1922 &ndash; January 13, 1999) was an American [[film director]] and [[film producer|producer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-buzz-kulik-1076884.html |title=Obituary: Buzz Kulik |work=The Independent |accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/25/arts/buzz-kulik-76-director-of-films-and-tv-programs.html |title=Buzz Kulik, 76, Director of Films and TV Programs |work=New York Times |accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref> He directed 72 films and television shows, including the landmark [[CBS]] television network anthology series ''[[Playhouse 90]]'' and several episodes of ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/mar/05/guardianobituaries |title=Buzz Kulik obituary |work=The Guardian |accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* ''[[Collector's Item (1958 film)|Collector's Item]]'' (1958 TV film)\n* ''[[Perry Mason Case of the Pint-Sized Client]]'' (1958 TV)\n* ''[[The Explosive Generation]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[Kings of Broadway]]'' (1962 TV film)\n* ''[[The Yellow Canary]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Ready for the People]]'' (1964)\n* ''[[Warning Shot (1967 film)|Warning Shot]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[Campo 44]]'' (1967 TV film)\n* ''[[Sergeant Ryker]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[Villa Rides]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[Riot (1969 film)|Riot]]