 short story writers]]\n[[Category:Anthony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Booker authors' division]]\n[[Category:British autobiographers]]\n[[Category:British detective writers]]\n[[Category:British women in World War I]]\n[[Category:British women short story writers]]\n[[Category:Burials in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:English crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English mystery writers]]\n[[Category:English short story writers]]\n[[Category:English women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Female nurses in World War I]]\n[[Category:Female wartime nurses]]\n[[Category:Formerly missing people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Detection Club]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in England]]\n[[Category:People from Cholsey]]\n[[Category:People from Sunningdale]]\n[[Category:People from Torquay]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous women writers]]\n[[Category:Temporary disappearances]]\n[[Category:Wives of knights]]\n[[Category:Women mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Women historical novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers of historical mysteries]]\n", "name_user": "RLO1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agatha_Christie"}
{"title_page": "2020 stock market crash", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n<!--<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic bear market|2=Talk:2020 stock market not crashed#Requested move 14 March 2020 }}\n</noinclude>-->{{Ongoing|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing stock market crash in 2020}}\n{{Infobox event|title=2020 stock market crash\n|image=Stock market crash (2020).svg\n|Image_Caption=Movement of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average|DJIA]] between January 2017 and March 2020, showing the all-time high on 12 February, and the subsequent crash during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]\n|map=Movement of the DJIA 2-19-2020\u20133-17-2020.svg\n|map_caption=Movement of the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average|DJIA]] between the day before the crash and [[2020 stock market crash#Black Monday II (16 March)|Black Monday II]]\n|date=20 February 2020 \u2013 ongoing\n|type=[[Stock market crash]]\n|cause=*[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]]-induced market instability \n*[[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Failure to renew an OPEC+ deal]]\n*[[Corporate debt bubble]]\n*[[Recession]] fears\n*[[Market liquidity]] crisis\n|outcome=*Sharp rise in [[unemployment]]\n*Collapse of the [[tourism]] industry\n*Collapse of the [[hospitality industry]]\n*Collapse of the [[price of oil]]\n*Destabilization and collapse of the [[energy industry]]\n*Increase in [[government debt]]\n*Major downturn in [[consumerism]]}}\n\nThe '''2020 stock market crash''', also called the  '''Coronavirus crash''', is a global [[stock market crash]] that began on 20 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Samuelson |first=Robert J. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/what-crash-2020-means/ |title=What Crash of 2020 Means |date=12 March 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311201743/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/what-crash-2020-means/ |archive-date=11 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wearden (earlier) |first=Graeme |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live |title=Wall Street and FTSE 100 plunge on worst day since 1987 \u2013 as it happened |date=12 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=12 March 2020 |last2=Jolly (now) |first2=Jasper |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312093531/https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/mar/12/stock-markets-tumble-trump-europe-travel-ban-ecb-christine-lagarde-business-live |archive-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/10/stock-market-crash-2020-everything-you-need-to-kno.aspx |title=Stock Market Crash 2020: Everything You Need to Know |last=Williams |first=Sean |date=10 March 2020 |website=The Motley Fool |language=en |access-date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312125019/https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/03/10/stock-market-crash-2020-everything-you-need-to-kno.aspx |archive-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 12 February, the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]], the [[NASDAQ Composite]], and [[S&P 500 Index]] all finished at [[Maxima and minima|record highs]] (while the NASDAQ and S&P 500 reached subsequent record highs on 19 February).<ref name=\"CNBC Dow 2-12-2020\" /><ref name=\"CNBC Dow 2-19-2020\" /> From 24 to 28 February, stock markets worldwide reported their largest one-week declines since the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 financial crisis]],<ref name=\"CNBC World 2-28-2020\" /><ref name=\"CNBC Dow 2-27-2020\" /><ref name=\"CNBC Europe 2-28-2020\" /> thus entering a [[Correction (stock market)|correction]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2020/02/27/dow-markets-plunge-correction-coronavirus/4889977002/ |title=Dow plunges 1,191 points, its biggest one-day point drop, as coronavirus fears escalate |last=Menton |first=Jessica |date=27 February 2020 |website=USA TODAY |language=en-US |access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/stocks-open-sharply-lower-dow-10-below-recent-record-high |title=Stock market enters a correction, down 10% from recent peak |last=Peltz |first=James F. |date=27 February 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |access-date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304060616/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/stocks-open-sharply-lower-dow-10-below-recent-record-high |archive-date=4 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/28/7-major-asia-pacific-markets-have-tumbled-into-correction-territory.html|title=Seven major Asia-Pacific markets have tumbled into correction territory|last=Huang|first=Eustance|date=2020-02-28|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229141124/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/28/7-major-asia-pacific-markets-have-tumbled-into-correction-territory.html|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Global markets into early March became extremely volatile, with large swings occurring in global markets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://mynorthwest.com/1748051/dow-industrials-surge-500-points-extending-volatile-streak/? |title=Asian shares rise following stimulus-led surge on Wall St |date=4 March 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |website=MyNorthwest |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305173545/https://mynorthwest.com/1748051/dow-industrials-surge-500-points-extending-volatile-streak/ |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-volatile-is-the-coronavirus-stricken-stock-market-after-the-worst-week-since-2008-the-dow-is-now-on-pace-for-its-best-week-since-2011-2020-03-04 |title=Wild stock-market swings are 'emotionally and intellectually wearing' on Wall Street |last=DeCambre |first=Mark |date=7 March 2020 |website=MarketWatch |language=en-US |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305050708/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-volatile-is-the-coronavirus-stricken-stock-market-after-the-worst-week-since-2008-the-dow-is-now-on-pace-for-its-best-week-since-2011-2020-03-04 |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 9&nbsp;March, most global markets reported severe contractions, mainly in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and an [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|oil price war between Russia and the OPEC countries led by Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314180258/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Business |first=Laura He, Clare Duffy and Julia Horowitz, CNN |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/08/investing/stock-dow-futures-coronavirus/index.html |title=US stocks halted after falling 7%. Global stocks plunge as oil crashes and coronavirus fear spreads |access-date=15 March 2020 |website=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314153658/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/08/investing/stock-dow-futures-coronavirus/index.html |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> This became colloquially known as Black Monday I, and at the time was the worst drop since the [[Great Recession]] in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/stock-markets-ftse-100-oil-prices-coronavirus-black-monday-a4382156.html |title=Black Monday: Fourth biggest City fall as virus panic hits markets |last=Prynn |first=Jonathon |last2=English |first2=Simon |date=9 March 2020 |website=Evening Standard |language=en |access-date=13 March 2020 |last3=Murphy |first3=Joe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311005736/https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/stock-markets-ftse-100-oil-prices-coronavirus-black-monday-a4382156.html |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Partington |first=Richard |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |title=Global stock markets post biggest falls since 2008 financial crisis |date=9 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 March 2020 |last2=Wearden |first2=Graeme |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312232659/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/09/global-stock-markets-post-biggest-falls-since-2008-financial-crisis |archive-date=12 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nThree days after Black Monday I there was another drop, Black Thursday, where stocks across Europe and North America fell more than 9%. [[Wall Street]] experienced its largest single-day percentage drop since [[Black Monday (1987)|Black Monday]] in 1987, and the [[FTSE MIB]] of the [[Borsa Italiana]] fell nearly 17%, becoming the worst-hit market during Black Thursday.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ansa.it/english/news/business/2020/03/12/milan-bourse-closes-almost-17-down_cd2da817-ad7d-46c8-a2ae-74071926e96c.html |title=Milan bourse closes almost 17% down - English |date=12 March 2020 |website=ANSA.it |language=en |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318211632/http://www.ansa.it/english/news/business/2020/03/12/milan-bourse-closes-almost-17-down_cd2da817-ad7d-46c8-a2ae-74071926e96c.html |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.icis.com/explore/resources/news/2020/03/12/10481846/europe-crude-petchems-prices-extend-losses-as-stocks-suffer-black-thursday |title=Europe crude, petchems prices extend losses as stocks suffer 'Black Thursday' |last=Lopez |first=Jonathan |date=12 March 2020 |website=Icis |language=en-US |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322160627/https://www.icis.com/explore/resources/news/2020/03/12/10481846/europe-crude-petchems-prices-extend-losses-as-stocks-suffer-black-thursday |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/dow-biggest-point-drop-ever-disney-apple/ |title=Dow Suffers Biggest Point Drop Ever, as Disney and Apple Fall Hard |last=Burch |first=Sean |date=12 March 2020 |website=TheWrap |language=en-US |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322160623/https://www.thewrap.com/dow-biggest-point-drop-ever-disney-apple/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite a temporary rally on 13&nbsp;March (with markets posting their best day since 2008), all three Wall Street indexes fell more than 12% when markets re-opened on 16&nbsp;March.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Business |first=By CNN |url=https://www.cnn.com/business/live-news/stock-market-news-today-031320/index.html |title=Stock market today: Live updates on the Dow, S&P 500, companies and more |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |language=en |website=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316225316/https://www.cnn.com/business/live-news/stock-market-news-today-031320/index.html |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/what-happened-to-the-stock-market-monday-stocks-plunge-despite-fed-stimulus.html |title=Here's what happened to the stock market on Monday |last=Imbert |first=Fred |date=16 March 2020 |website=CNBC |language=en |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317030511/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/what-happened-to-the-stock-market-monday-stocks-plunge-despite-fed-stimulus.html |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> At least one benchmark [[stock market index]] in all [[Group of Seven|G7]] countries and 14 of the [[G20]] countries have been declared to be in [[bear market]]s.\n\n{{As of|March 2020}}, global stocks have seen a downturn of at least 25% during the crash, and 30% in most [[G20]] nations. On March 20, [[Goldman Sachs]] warned that the [[Economy of the United States|US GDP]] would shrink 29% by the end of the 2nd quarter of 2020, and that unemployment could skyrocket to at least 9%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/us-gdp-drop-record-2q-amid-coronavirus-recession-goldman-sachs-2020-3-1029018308|title=Goldman Sachs now says US GDP will shrink 24% next quarter amid the coronavirus pandemic - which would be 2.5 times bigger than any decline in history {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326202721/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/us-gdp-drop-record-2q-amid-coronavirus-recession-goldman-sachs-2020-3-1029018308|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Prime Minister of Australia|Australian Prime Minister]] [[Scott Morrison]] has called the looming [[Financial crisis|economic crisis]] 'akin to the [[Great Depression]]'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/economy/echoes-of-great-depression-as-australian-jobless-queue-for-help|title=Echoes of Great Depression as Australian jobless queue for help|last=hermesauto|date=2020-03-23|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324214533/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/economy/echoes-of-great-depression-as-australian-jobless-queue-for-help|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n=== Causes ===\n[[File:SARS-CoV-2 49531042877.jpg|thumb|Scanning electron microscope image of [[SARS-CoV-2]] (centre, yellow)]]\nThe 2020 stock market crash occurred during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], one of the most impactful [[pandemic]]s since the [[Spanish flu]] in 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/onpoint/2020/03/24/lessons-coronavirus-1918-flu-pandemic|title=What The 1918 Flu Pandemic Teaches Us About The Coronavirus Outbreak|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Rising fears and global economic shutdown due to the [[Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|economic impact of COVID-19]] is believed to be a main cause of the stock market crash, though many experts have argued that it is an 'accelerant' rather than a sole core reason behind the crash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5793506/a-stock-market-crash-was-coming-coronavirus-was-just-the-spark/|title=A Market Crash Was Coming, Coronavirus Was Just the Spark|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302220819/https://time.com/5793506/a-stock-market-crash-was-coming-coronavirus-was-just-the-spark/|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capital.com/stock-market-crash-2020|title=Top three reasons behind the stock market crash 2020: is it coronavirus, oil price war or vanished liquidity?|website=capital.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== 10\u201314 February ==\nOn Monday, 10 February 2020, [[Asia-Pacific]] stock markets closed up while European stock markets closed mixed,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Huang|first=Eustance|title=Hong Kong stocks lead gains in Asia as investors weigh economic impact of coronavirus|date=10 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/11/asia-markets-coronavirus-china-economy-currencies-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Elliot|last2=Taylor|first2=Chloe|title=European markets close mixed as coronavirus concerns linger; NMC Health up 32%|date=10 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/10/european-markets-coronavirus-crisis-continues-to-weigh.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> with the Dow Jones Industrial Average, the NASDAQ Composite, and S&P 500 also closing up (and the NASDAQ Composite and S&P 500 at record highs).<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Imbert|first1=Fred|title=Dow jumps 170 points, Amazon leads S&P 500 and Nasdaq to record highs|date=10 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/10/us-futures-point-to-cautious-open-as-investors-monitor-coronavirus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Price of oil|Oil prices]] rose by 1%,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kearney|first=Laila|title=Oil prices rise about 1%, up from 13-month low as virus cases slow|date=10 February 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/global-oil/oil-prices-slip-as-coronavirus-concerns-linger-idUSL4N2AI0F5|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> while the [[Yield (finance)|yields]] on 10-year and 30-year [[United States Treasury security#Treasury note|U.S. Treasury securities]] fell to 1.54% and 2.02% (with part of the [[Yield curve#Inverted yield curve|yield curve inverting]] as the 10-year yield fell below the 3-month yield at 1.56%).<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Li|first1=Yun|last2=Amaro|first2=Silvia|title=Treasury yields fall as coronavirus fears linger|date=10 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/10/us-treasury-yields-move-higher-ahead-of-trump-2021-budget.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> On 11 February, Asia-Pacific and European stock markets closed up,<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Huang|first1=Eustance|title=Chinese stocks surge as investors shrug off virus fears; Softbank surges nearly 12%|date=11 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/12/asia-markets-coronavirus-wall-street-record-highs-the-fed-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Elliot|last2=Taylor|first2=Chloe|title=European markets close higher as coronavirus remains in focus; Tui up 13%|date=11 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/11/european-markets-set-for-higher-open-as-coronavirus-remains-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> while the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed flat but the NASDAQ Composite and S&P 500 closed at new record highs.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Imbert|first1=Fred|title=S&P 500 and Nasdaq eke out fresh record closing highs|date=11 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/11/us-futures-point-to-higher-open-on-wall-street-with-virus-and-earnings-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Oil prices rose by 2%,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Oil jumps more than 2% as slowdown in new China coronavirus cases eases fuel demand concerns|date=11 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/12/oil-markets-coronavirus-chinese-demand-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> while yields on 10-year and 30-year U.S. Treasury securities rose to 1.59% and 2.05% respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Franck|first1=Thomas|last2=Meredith|first2=Sam|title=Treasury yields rise after Powell's first day of testimony on Capitol Hill|date=11 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/11/us-bonds-treasury-yields-and-jerome-powells-testimony-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 February, Asia-Pacific stock markets closed down while European stock markets closed up,<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Huang|first1=Eustance|title=Chinese stocks slip as new coronavirus cases in Hubei spike|date=12 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/13/asia-markets-wall-street-record-coronavirus-currencies-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Elliot|last2=Taylor|first2=Chloe|title=European markets close higher despite coronavirus fears; Heineken up 6%|date=12 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/12/europe-markets-investors-monitor-coronavirus-updates.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> while the Dow Jones Industrial Average, NASDAQ Composite, and S&P 500 all closed at new record highs.<ref name=\"CNBC Dow 2-12-2020\">{{Cite news|last1=Imbert|first1=Fred|title=Dow jumps more than 250 points to a record|date=12 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/12/us-futures-point-to-higher-open-after-stocks-hit-fresh-record-highs.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Oil prices rose by 1%,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kumar|first=Devika Krishna|title=Oil prices climb on prospects for deeper OPEC+ output cuts|date=12 February 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-oil/oil-prices-climb-on-prospects-for-deeper-opec-output-cuts-idUSKBN20707C|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> while the yield on 10-year and 30-year U.S. Treasury securities rose to 1.63% and 2.09% respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Li|first1=Yun|last2=Meredith|first2=Sam|title=Treasury yields jump for a second day as investors return to risk assets|date=12 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/12/us-bonds-treasury-yields-in-focus-as-coronavirus-concerns-persist.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 February, Asia-Pacific stock markets rose while European and U.S. stock markets closed down,<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Huang|first1=Eustance|title=Asia stocks mostly rise as investors mull virus impact; Singapore flags risk of recession|date=13 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/14/asia-markets-coronavirus-corporate-earnings-currencies-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Chloe|title=European markets close lower as coronavirus concerns persist; oil and gas stocks lead losses|date=13 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/13/european-markets-set-for-lower-open-coronavirus-earnings-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Imbert|first1=Fred|title=Dow drops more than 100 points, slips from record high as reported coronavirus cases jump|date=13 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/13/us-futures-point-to-lower-open-on-wall-street.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> with oil prices rising but yields on 10-year and 30-year U.S. Treasury securities falling to 1.58% and 2.04% respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saefong|first=Myra P.|title=Oil prices post a modest gain as traders weigh coronavirus, OPEC|date=13 February 2020|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|website=[[MarketWatch]]|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/oil-prices-post-a-modest-gain-as-traders-weigh-coronavirus-opec-2020-02-13|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Li|first1=Yun|last2=Meredith|first2=Sam|title=Treasury yields fall after surge in reported coronavirus cases|date=13 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/13/us-bonds-treasury-yields-in-focus-after-surge-in-coronavirus-cases.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Bank of Mexico]] cut its [[overnight rate]] by 25 [[basis point]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Esposito|first=Anthony|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-economy-rates/flagging-weaker-growth-mexico-central-bank-cuts-interest-rate-again-idUSKBN2072OI|title=Flagging weaker growth, Mexico central bank cuts interest rate again|date=13 February 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220053443/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-economy-rates/flagging-weaker-growth-mexico-central-bank-cuts-interest-rate-again-idUSKBN2072OI|archive-date=20 February 2020|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]}}</ref> On 14 February, Asia-Pacific stock markets closed up while European stock markets finished with mixed closings,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hyerczyk|first=James|title=Asian Stocks Mostly Higher; Singapore PM Sees Possible Recession from Coronavirus Impact|date=14 February 2020|publisher=[[Verizon Media]]|website=[[Yahoo! Finance]]|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/asian-stocks-mostly-higher-singapore-092444581.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Chloe|title=Europe markets close mixed as traders weigh earnings, coronavirus; RBS falls 7%|date=14 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/14/european-markets-coronavirus-earnings-remain-in-focus.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> and the Dow Jones Industrial Average, NASDAQ Composite, and S&P 500 closed up (and net positive on the week).<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Imbert|first1=Fred|title=Stocks close little changed, but post a gain for the week|date=14 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/14/stock-market-coronavirus-outbreak-in-focus-on-wall-street.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Oil prices were steady (but closed up on the week),<ref>{{Cite news|title=Oil prices steady, on course for weekly gain|date=14 February 2020|work=[[The Economic Times]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/commodities/news/oil-prices-steady-on-course-for-weekly-gain/articleshow/74134364.cms|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> while yields on 10-year and 30-year U.S. Treasury securities fell to 1.58% and 2.03% respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Franck|first1=Thomas|last2=Meredith|first2=Sam|title=Treasury yields fall after weak retail sales data spurs economic unease|date=14 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/14/us-bonds-treasury-yields-in-focus-as-coronavirus-concerns-linger.html|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== 17\u201321 February ==\n\nOn Monday, 17 February 2020, Asia-Pacific stock markets closed down but European stock markets closed up,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tan|first=Weizhen|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/18/asia-stocks-apple-revenue-forecast-hsbc-earnings-coronavirus.html|title=Asia stocks mostly tumble as Apple issues revenue warning; HSBC earnings miss expectations|date=17 February 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223192105/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/18/asia-stocks-apple-revenue-forecast-hsbc-earnings-coronavirus.html|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Elliot|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/17/europe-markets-traders-monitor-coronavirus-and-earnings.html|title=European stocks close higher as traders monitor coronavirus|date=17 February 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301050431/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/17/europe-markets-traders-monitor-coronavirus-and-earnings.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while U.S. stock markets were closed in observance of [[Washington's Birthday|Presidents Day]].<ref name=\"MarketWatch Dow 2-17-2020\">{{cite news|last=Oh|first=Sunny|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/heres-which-markets-are-open-on-presidents-day-2020-02-14|title=Here's which markets are open, and closed, this Presidents Day|date=17 February 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|website=[[MarketWatch]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218023424/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/heres-which-markets-are-open-on-presidents-day-2020-02-14|archive-date=18 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Oil prices fell,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jaganathan|first=Jessica|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/global-oil/oil-prices-slip-as-coronavirus-concerns-linger-idUSL4N2AI0F5|title=Oil prices slip as coronavirus concerns linger|date=18 February 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|access-date=26 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323170628/https://www.reuters.com/article/global-oil/oil-prices-slip-as-coronavirus-concerns-linger-idUSL4N2AI0F5|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while the yield on 10-year U.S. Treasury securities fell to 1.59%.<ref>{{Cite news|last=La Monica|first=Paul R.|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/17/investing/bond-rates-yields-inflation-economy/index.html|title=How low can bond rates go?|date=17 February 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]|website=[[CNN Business]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222221007/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/17/investing/bond-rates-yields-inflation-economy/index.html|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 18 February, Asia-Pacific stock markets closed up,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Tan|first=Weizhen|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/asia-markets-china-return-to-production-apple-shares-oil-and-currencies.html|title=Asia markets bounce back as investors monitor China's return to production|date=18 February 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224201946/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/asia-markets-china-return-to-production-apple-shares-oil-and-currencies.html|archive-date=24 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while European stock markets, the Dow Jones Industrial Average, NASDAQ Composite, and S&P 500 all closed down.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Elliot|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/18/europe-markets-apple-warns-on-coronavirus-hit-hsbc-misses-on-profits.html|title=Europe stocks close lower as Apple warns of coronavirus revenue hit|date=18 February 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301050423/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/18/europe-markets-apple-warns-on-coronavirus-hit-hsbc-misses-on-profits.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC Dow 2-18-2020\">{{Cite news|last=Imbert|first=Fred|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/18/stock-market-wall-street-in-focus-after-apple-issues-revenue-warning.html|title=Dow falls for a third day, dropping 165 points after Apple's coronavirus warning|date=18 February 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220201612/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/18/stock-market-wall-street-in-focus-after-apple-issues-revenue-warning.html|archive-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Oil prices rose by more than 2%,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kearney|first=Laila|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-oil/oil-up-more-than-2-on-slowing-coronavirus-cases-u-s-move-on-venezuela-idUSKBN20D059|title=Oil up more than 2% on slowing coronavirus cases, U.S. move on Venezuela|date=18 February 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]}}</ref> while the yields on 10-year and 30-year U.S. Treasury securities fell to 1.54% and 1.99%.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Li|first1=Yun|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/18/us-bonds-treasury-yields-in-focus-as-coronavirus-fears-persist.html|title=Treasury yields fall as coronavirus fears persist|date=18 February 2020|access-date=21 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|last2=Meredith|first2=Sam|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221212103/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/18/us-bonds-treasury-yields-in-focus-as-coronavirus-fears-persist.html|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Ministry of Finance (Singapore)|Singaporean Finance Minister]] [[Heng Swee Keat]] announced a $4.5 billion [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] program.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Geddie|first1=John|last2=Aravindan|first2=Aradhana|title=Singapore plans biggest budget deficit in years to meet virus threat|date=18 February 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-singapore-economy-budget/singapore-plans-biggest-budget-deficit-in-years-to-meet-virus-threat-idUSKBN20C0P2|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 February, Asia-Pacific and European stock markets closed mostly up,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Huang|first=Eustance|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/asia-markets-china-lpr-australia-jobs-data-currencies-in-focus.html|title=Chinese stocks surge as the country cuts its loan prime rate|date=19 February 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225212042/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/asia-markets-china-lpr-australia-jobs-data-currencies-in-focus.html|archive-date=25 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Elliot|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/europe-markets-new-cases-of-coronavirus-slow-eu-to-launch-ai-proposals.html|title=European stocks close higher as investors monitor coronavirus, economic data|date=19 February 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301050416/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/europe-markets-new-cases-of-coronavirus-slow-eu-to-launch-ai-proposals.html|archive-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while the Dow Jones Industrial Average finished up and the NASDAQ Composite and the S&P 500 finished at record highs.<ref name=\"CNBC Dow 2-19-2020\">{{Cite news|last=Imbert|first=Fred|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/stock-market-wall-street-in-focus-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=S&P 500 and Nasdaq jump to record highs, Dow climbs more than 100 points|date=19 February 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223134320/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/stock-market-wall-street-in-focus-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Oil prices rose by another 2%,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/oil-markets-coronavirus-in-focus.html|title=Oil rises more than 2% as coronavirus fears ease|date=19 February 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224201924/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/oil-markets-coronavirus-in-focus.html|archive-date=24 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> while yields on 10-year and 30-year U.S. Treasury securities fell to 1.56% and 2.00% respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Li|first=Yun|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/us-bonds-treasury-yields-in-focus-as-part-of-the-yield-curve-inverts.html|title=Treasury yields dip after Fed minutes highlight coronavirus risk|date=19 February 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223220100/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/us-bonds-treasury-yields-in-focus-as-part-of-the-yield-curve-inverts.html|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[People's Bank of China]] and the [[Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey]] cut their [[Repurchase agreement|repo rates]] by 10 and 50 [[basis point]]s respectively,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Erkoyun|first=Ezgi|url=https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/turkish-central-bank-cuts-key-rate-by-50-basis-points-2020-02-19|title=Turkish central bank cuts key rate by 50 basis points|date=19 February 2020|access-date=6 March 2020|publisher=[[Nasdaq, Inc.]]|last2=Kucukgocmen|first2=Ali|website=[[Nasdaq|Nasdaq.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Yen Nee|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/coronavirus-chinas-pboc-cuts-benchmark-lending-rate-loan-prime-rate.html|title=China cuts benchmark lending rates amid coronavirus outbreak|date=19 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226132549/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/coronavirus-chinas-pboc-cuts-benchmark-lending-rate-loan-prime-rate.html|archive-date=26 February 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]}}</ref> while the [[Central Bank of Argentina]] cut its [[bank rate]] by 400 basis points.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-argentina-rates/argentina-slashes-benchmark-interest-rate-to-40-seventh-cut-since-december-idUSKBN20D2TN|title=Argentina slashes benchmark interest rate to 40%; seventh cut since December|date=19 February 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220113942/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-argentina-rates/argentina-slashes-benchmark-interest-rate-to-40-seventh-cut-since-december-idUSKBN20D2TN|archive-date=20 February 2020|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 20&nbsp;February, stock markets worldwide closed mostly down,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Huang|first=Eustance|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/21/asia-markets-coronavirus-oil-currencies-in-focus.html|title=China stocks rise as Beijing says work resumption is speeding up|date=20 February 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226223635/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/21/asia-markets-coronavirus-oil-currencies-in-focus.html|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Elliot|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/european-stocks-headed-for-lower-open-despite-coronavirus-slowdown-in-china.html|title=European stocks close lower as investors monitor coronavirus and earnings; Air France KLM down 3%|date=20 February 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|last2=Ellyat|first2=Holly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302071658/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/european-stocks-headed-for-lower-open-despite-coronavirus-slowdown-in-china.html|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC Dow 2-20-2020\">{{Cite news|last=Imbert|first=Fred|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/us-futures-point-to-slightly-lower-open-after-new-highs-on-wall-street.html|title=Dow falls more than 100 points after suffering a sudden midday sell-off that confused traders|date=20 February 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223220210/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/us-futures-point-to-slightly-lower-open-after-new-highs-on-wall